{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}

'''Juan Armando Roque''' (born February 6, 1974)<ref>{{cite web | title = All-Time Players: Juan Roque | publisher = [[National Football League]] | url = http://www.nfl.com/players/juanroque/profile?id=ROQ402541 | accessdate = June 3, 2010 }}</ref> is a former [[American football]] [[offensive tackle]] who played three years for the [[National Football League]]'s (NFL) [[Detroit Lions]] and played one season for the [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]]. Roque is currently a [[Color commentator|color analyst]] for [[Fox Sports Arizona]] for [[Arizona State University]] football games.

==Beginnings==
Roque was born in [[San Diego, California]], to Armando and Maria Roque. Shortly after Juan's birth Armando and Maria moved to the Roques' native Mexico, living in [[Coatzacoalcos, Veracruz]]. When Juan was three the Roques returned to California and eventually resided in [[Ontario, California|Ontario]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Garrity | first = John | title = Mighty Like A Warrior | journal = [[Sports Illustrated]] | date = December 30, 1996 | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1009294/2/index.htm | accessdate = October 4, 2009 }}</ref>

==High school==
Roque attended [[Ontario High School (California)|Ontario High School]] and played on its offensive line.<ref>{{cite news | last = Brewster | first = Louis | title = Mosley's antics not surprising | work = San Bernadino Sun | date = September 21, 2009 | url = http://www.sbsun.com/sports/ci_13390326 | accessdate = June 3, 2010 }}</ref> Coming out of high school, Roque was recruited by numerous colleges;<ref name="keeping2">{{cite news | last = Gustkey | first = Earl | title = Keeping His Commitments: Arizona State Lineman Roque More Than Makes Good on Promise to Complete Eligibility for Arizona State (page 2) | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = December 30, 1996 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-30/sports/sp-13938_1_arizona-state/2 | accessdate = June 3, 2010 }}</ref> these included [[University of Southern California|USC]] and [[Washington State University|Washington State]].<ref name="keeping">{{cite news | last = Gustkey | first = Earl | title = Keeping His Commitments: Arizona State Lineman Roque More Than Makes Good on Promise to Complete Eligibility for Arizona State (page 3) | work = Los Angeles Times | date = December 30, 1996 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-30/sports/sp-13938_1_arizona-state/3 | accessdate = June 3, 2010 }}</ref> Initially Roque verbally committed to USC but withdrew the commitment and decided to sign his [[letter of intent]] with [[Arizona State University]] to play for incoming head coach [[Bruce Snyder]].<ref name="keeping"/><ref>{{cite news | last = Metcalfe | first = Jeff | title = Former ASU coach Snyder dies | work = [[The Arizona Republic]] | date = April 13, 2009 | url = http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2009/04/13/20090413asusnyder.html | accessdate = June 24, 2010 }}</ref> Roque was initially recruited as a defensive lineman.<ref>{{cite news | title = Spring Football Preview | work = [[The Register-Guard]] | date = April 29, 1992 | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jH8VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oesDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5880,6403968 | accessdate = June 24, 2010 }}</ref>

==College==
Soon after arriving at Arizona State, Roque was moved to offensive tackle and [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] during the [[1992 NCAA Division I-A football season|1992 season]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Friend | first = Tom | title = In the End, Pancakes Will Tell the Tale for Two Tackles | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = December 31, 1996 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/1996/12/31/sports/in-the-end-pancakes-will-tell-the-tale-for-two-tackles.html | accessdate = June 24, 2010 }}</ref> By his sophomore season, 1994, Roque had gained a starting spot for Arizona State at [[Guard (American football)|left guard]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Missildine | first = Harry | title = Devil 'D' surely not soft | work = [[Moscow-Pullman Daily News]] | date = October 21, 1994 | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VIokAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1NAFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3223,2615629 | accessdate = June 24, 2010 }}</ref> 

In 1995 Roque was named as a pre-season All-West lineman, and honorable mention All-American, by ''Street & Smith's''.<ref>{{cite book | title = Street & Smith's College Football 1995 | publisher = Street & Smith's | date = 1995 | location = New York City | pages = 22, 36 }}</ref> Following the season, he was named to the All Pacific-10 Conference first team and was a second team All-American by ''The Sporting News''.<ref name="hall">{{cite web | title = Juan Roque, Mike Sodders lead 2009 ASU Sports Hall of Fame Class | publisher = [[Arizona State University]] | date = September 11, 2009 | url = http://asunews.asu.edu/20090911_Athletics_HOF | accessdate = October 4, 2009 }}</ref>

Before the 1996 season Roque was considered as a contender for the [[Outland Trophy]] as best interior lineman in the country.<ref>{{cite news | title = Sports Weekend <U+2013> The Key Games In College Football: Game Of The Week | work = Los Angeles Times | date = September 6, 1996 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-06/sports/sp-41145_1_college-football/2 | accessdate = July 15, 2010 }}</ref> In May 1996 Roque graduated from Arizona State, earning a Latin American history degree.<ref name="keeping2"/> Roque started all 11 games for the Sun Devils that season, helping the team go 11<U+2013>0 in the regular season.<ref name="hall"/> Notable victories that season were a 19<U+2013>0 upset of number one-ranked Nebraska,<ref>{{cite news | last = Dufresne | first = Chris | title = Top-Ranked USC in for Devil of a Time? | work = Los Angeles Times | date = September 29, 2005 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2005/sep/29/sports/sp-dufcol29 | accessdate = July 15, 2010 }}</ref> a come from behind victory over UCLA, a [[Overtime (sports)|double overtime]] win against USC, and a 52-14 rout of the Univrsity of Arizona in [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]]. Arizona State won the Pacific-10 Conference championship for the second time in school history and earned a [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] berth with a 35-7 victory against California. Roque received numerous honors that year. He was a consensus [[All-American]], All Pacific-10 Conference first team member for the second year in a row, runner-up for the [[Lombardi Award]], and was an Outland Trophy finalist. Roque started in the [[1997 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] on January 1, 1997 against [[Ohio State University]]. The second ranked Sun Devils, despite a strong effort by [[quarterback]] [[Jake Plummer]], lost possibly one of the best Rose Bowl games ever played 20<U+2013>17. Roque was selected to play in the [[East<U+2013>West Shrine Game]] in [[Palo Alto, California]] and the [[Senior Bowl]] in [[Mobile, Alabama]]. Roque was invited to participate in the 1997 [[NFL Scouting Combine|NFL Combine]] in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]] and did so.

==Professional football==
During the [[1997 NFL Draft]] Roque was selected by the Detroit Lions in the second round (35th overall).<ref>{{cite web | title = 1997 NFL Draft | publisher = [[Pro Football Reference]] | url = http://www.pro-football-reference.com/draft/1997.htm | accessdate = October 4, 2009 }}</ref> During his rookie year Roque played in 12 games. For the [[Thanksgiving Classic|Thanksgiving Day game]] against the [[Chicago Bears]], Roque earned the starting nod at right tackle. In the nationally televised game, Roque played well but in the fourth quarter suffered a serious knee injury that sidelined him for the remainder of the season. Roque had the knee surgically repaired in December 1997.

Roque did not play in 1998 as he spent the entire year on [[Injured reserve list|injured reserve]] due to lingering effects from the knee injury. Roque underwent surgery again in December.

In 1999 Roque earned a starting position at right tackle. He started the first two games and helped the Lions earn a 2<U+2013>0 record. Roque spent the rest of the season on the active<U+2013>inactive list and played against the [[Washington Redskins]] during the [[1999<U+2013>2000 NFL playoffs#Wild Card playoffs|Wild Card playoff game]] in January 2000. Roque was released by the Lions before the [[2000 NFL season|2000 season]].

In 2001 Roque signed a contract to play for the Toronto Argonauts of the Canadian Football League. Roque started all 18 games at right tackle and helped pave the way for the CFL's top rusher, [[Michael Jenkins (Canadian football)|Michael Jenkins]].  

==Post-football==
Since 2007 Roque has worked as a color commentator for television broadcasts of Arizona State games on [[Fox Sports Arizona]].<ref>{{cite news | title = FSN Arizona to show ASU's first 2 games | work = [[East Valley Tribune]] | date = August 21, 2009 | url = http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/story/143304 | accessdate = October 4, 2009 }}</ref> On October 17, 2009, Roque was inducted into the Arizona State University Sports Hall of Fame.<ref name="hall"/> Roque resides in [[Chandler, Arizona]] and is an avid Arizona State supporter. Roque is currently involved in many ventures such as Camp74, which will focus on the development of young offensive linemen, and works for Hock Law Group as a [[legal administrator]].

